"The great and powerful" leads to Moscow: migrants save money for language
While members of Parliament and civil rights activist in discussing, what benefits it brings the law on mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals Act already with fake certificates
Every year come 13 million migrant workers to Moscow, Saint Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to make money for the upkeep of the families remaining in the home.
On December 1, an Act entered into force which according to each migrant must take a test that certifies knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this applies only to migrants who want to work in the service sector, the municipal housing sector and retail.
However, the tests with time according to Federal Migration Office should be in future for all migrant workers mandatory.
Here you must play not only language tests but also tests in Russia's history and the basics of the legislation.
Language skills must be assigned to both the receipt and the extension of the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is an official language.
Also, people who have received their training certificates and diplomas before the disintegration of the USSR in 1991 are exempt from this law.
Meaning, problems and protection of the rights
The whole of the examination bodies is the Russian University of people's friendship, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities are under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute of Russian, language.
The migrants can take the tests in all the cities; already more than 160 corresponding centres were opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the federal migration service.
Civil libertarians, however, was before the entry into force of the law in the press several times the following question: what actually brings the whole thing?
What changes is the requirement to have language skills, both for the Russians and for the migrant workers?
First of all, say the migration authority spokesman, matter it to reduce the number of forced laborers.
"Many now speak about the protection of the rights of migrant workers", says the head of the representation of the federal migration service in Tajikistan, Viktor Sebelew.
However, their rights must be protected prior to their departure.
Only an organized recruitment will solve the problems of foreign workers 90%.
Migrants encounter problems without professional, education, language skills and medical assessment.
